18:06.340 --> 18:14.140
This is Daryl Lane and Bill Vernon. Science fiction and fantasy author Piers
Anthony has been writing in these genres since the mid-60s. Anthony's apparent

18:14.140 --> 18:22.660
production was fairly low until 1977, when his work began appearing with
increasing frequency. Right. Since that apparently sudden explosion of effort in

18:22.660 --> 18:30.660
1977, some 18 Anthony volumes have appeared in print for the first time. But
Anthony did not suddenly begin writing at a brisker pace. He told us that he had

18:30.660 --> 18:38.420
been blacklisted by the publishing industry in the early 70s because he had
insisted on being paid fairly for his first published novel, Thone. The

18:38.420 --> 18:46.540
explosion of his works in print in 1977 was a result of his overcoming the
blacklisting. Here Anthony explains. I could only sell a portion of what I

18:46.540 --> 18:59.820
wrote. In fact, I was writing it. I piled up eight novels unsold so that in the
70s, say, 50% of my output was getting into print. But when I finally got

18:59.820 --> 19:09.680
through that, it finally became apparent to some of these publishers that I was
the one that was right, you see. See, the word was being spread by the

19:09.680 --> 19:19.320
blacklisters how difficult a writer I was to deal with and don't deal with this
guy and so on. It's just nothing but trouble. When I finally, when that passed

19:19.320 --> 19:28.980
and I got to working with editors who knew me personally and knew it wasn't so,
then I could sell everything I wrote. So now you're seeing everything I write.

19:29.100 --> 19:37.820
And it looks like an explosion, but I always was writing at that pace. I just
couldn't get it into print. Piers Anthony is actually a nom de plume utilizing

19:37.820 --> 19:46.820
only the author's first and second names. When we asked Anthony why he uses a
pen name, we found out it's due to some long-range planning. I decided on that

19:46.820 --> 19:58.160
before I ever sold a thing. And I said, supposing I write, and just supposing
I'm successful, and just supposing I get to be famous. Now, all of this was an

19:58.160 --> 20:08.640
awful lot of supposing. I mean, I hadn't even sold anything. I'd been trying for
several years and hadn't. I've heard about writers such as John D. MacDonald, a

20:08.640 --> 20:17.620
mystery writer, and he had to move several times because people would come in
and just drop in. They would assume that he had nothing better to do than to

20:17.620 --> 20:24.540
talk with every fan that dropped in on his address. And so he would have to move
so his address would be lost. It would take him two or three years to find him,

20:24.580 --> 20:35.480
and then they'd take up his time again. And why have this happen to me if I ever
get that well-known? The answer was to use the pen name. So I set up with the

20:35.480 --> 20:44.420
pen name from the outset, and it has protected me. I get a lot of fan mail. It
goes through the publisher. I don't get many people dropping in on me because

20:44.420 --> 20:51.400
they can't find me. They can look up in the phone book. There is, I don't know,
maybe there's somebody locally called Anthony that keeps getting people dropping

20:51.400 --> 21:01.740
in on him. It's not me, you see. So I have protected myself. If I want someone
to know who I am, I can tell them. But the stranger that just says, hey, gee,

21:01.800 --> 21:12.400
there's this writer. I think I'll drop in on him. He is unable to find me. And
so now I'm beginning to approach the sort of success that the pseudonym was

21:12.400 --> 21:21.120
prepared for. I really never thought I would get there. It was just saying
suppose. And I planned well. I'm having more success than I really believed I

21:21.120 --> 21:31.200
would have. And now my pen name is serving to protect me, to protect my time,
really. It's not that I mind talking with people. But, you know, there would be

21:31.200 --> 21:37.280
a lot of people that would just like to come. If there's a writer there, they
won't even have read anything by that author. They say, gee, that's a writer.

21:37.420 --> 21:45.240
I'll go talk to him. But I don't need that sort of thing. I'm willing to talk to
people that have read my works, that want to talk to me, ask me intelligent

21:45.240 --> 21:54.020
questions. And that people more like you, you see, I'm not willing to talk to
the man off the street who just has heard that I'm a writer. He doesn't even

21:54.020 --> 22:05.780
know what I'm writing about. But if there's a writer, he just wants to go and
talk to him and take up his time. So that's the reason, again, a rather

22:05.780 --> 22:14.520
commercial reason, if you will. But I think it's effective. We'll have more
about Piers Anthony on our next show.

